(92, 1, '2009-11-20 17:04:26', '2009-11-20 17:04:26', 'I have been meaning to do this for so long, but today ( mainly because I am bored of doing all other uni work) I have  finished setting up my blog.\n\nThe grand plan is to use this blog so that I can coherently keep a record of all my thoughts, ideas and inspirations as I go through my second year of uni. I initially wanted to have this finished by the start of term so i could have a full account of the year ahead but unfortunately that has not happened! but better late than never.\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'I Can&#039;t Believe It&#039;s The...', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'i-cant-believe-its-the', '', '', '2009-11-20 17:04:26', '2009-11-20 17:04:26', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/?p=92', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(94, 1, '2009-11-20 17:35:27', '2009-11-20 17:35:27', 'This semister we have three quite different projects on the go;\n\n<strong>1. PDP</strong>\n\nThis is the subject that brought me round to the idea of creating this blog.  To complete the module we need to keep a journal of our year at uni and try our best to piece together the creative thoughts we have as a way of explaining our work. Unfortunately my handwriting is barely legible and I have a tendency to loose note books so I came to the logical conclusion to post it on the web.\n\nAswel as the journal I need to write an illustrated essay based on one of six essay questions and give two presentations.\n\n<strong>2. Development of Graphical Media Process</strong>\n\nFor the main part of the semester ( 50% of the mark) I have to \" Create an innovative Selection of print based publicity material for the <a title=\"trumanbrewery\" href=\"http://www.trumanbrewery.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Old Truman Brewery</a> - Cultural Arts Centre London E1\"\n\nThis translates to a new; Visual Identify, Events Broadsheet, Invitation Card and  Guide Booklet.\n\n<strong>3.Photography</strong>\n\nFinally this semester we have a photography task. but that doesn\'t start till next wee so more about that to come...\n\n<p> </p>', 'The Story So Far...', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-story-so-far', '', '', '2009-11-20 17:35:27', '2009-11-20 17:35:27', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/?p=94', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(96, 1, '2009-11-20 17:48:36', '2009-11-20 17:48:36', 'Back in September we were given a two week starter project to ease us back into work.\n\nThe Brief was to create a postcard that reflects what you are like, but the catch is it must illustrate all eight of the following points.\n<ol>\n<li>An object or heirloom of significant importance</li>\n<li>An important date</li>\n<li>A luxury you cant live without</li>\n<li>A favourite food</li>\n<li>An old family photograph</li>\n<li>A birthmark/scar</li>\n<li>A favourite fictional character</li>\n<li>A pet aversion ( the thing you most love to hate)</li>\n</ol>\n[gallery]', 'Two Week Starter Project', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'two-week-starter-projectan', '', '', '2009-11-20 17:48:36', '2009-11-20 17:48:36', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/?p=96', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(188, 1, '2009-11-20 20:28:01', '2009-11-20 20:28:01', 'I was lucky enough to be whisked away to NewYork last week to celebrate my 21st birthday. Seeing as it is unlikely that I will be able to go again with the rest of my university class early next year I have tried to make the most of the opportunity this time round.I managed to visit the Museum of Art and Design, which I thoroughly enjoyed. One thing that did strike me about american museums is that they all seem to charge entrance fees. This seemed very unnatural from a british perspective seeing that the large majority of museums in the UK, and in Europe are donation based.\r\n\r\nGhost Stories - Nendo\r\n\r\nOne of my favorite exhibitions from the museum was “Ghost Stories” by Nendo. It consisted of several chairs aligned randomly on the floor. But due to a very clever bi of design he managed to substitute the wooden legs of the chair with plastic giving the illusion of the chairs floating in a eire mist. I think the reason I liked this piece so much is that it appears to trick the eye. At first glance you see chairs and wonder how the effect has been achieved. The use of contrasting materials and the process of allowing the audience to second guess your work is defiantly a quality I would like to achieve in some of my designs.\r\n\r\nThis Is For You - Rob Ryan\r\n\r\nThe second exhibition found interesting was that of Rob Ryan. Ryan had several piece on show but my favorite was a two story window hanging. I think that drew my attention first was the pure scale of the piece, the second was its intricacy. Although the media used was simple, the detail was not. What I liked most about the piece, apart from the elegance of the design its self, was the way it looked in the light. Because of the cutting you saw both the designs, media behind it (the window) and the shadow it cast.', 'New York New York!!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-york-new-york', '', '', '2010-10-25 15:32:22', '2010-10-25 15:32:22', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/?p=188', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(104, 1, '2009-12-09 23:27:09', '2009-12-09 23:27:09', 'The main project we are working on this semester is the rebranding of the Old Truman Gallery in bricklane, the gallery hosts wide range of events and exhibitons through out the year, and is rewnond for it\'s colourful cultural heritage. The site where the gallery now stands has it\'s roots burried deep in the history of the east end.\r\n\r\nVery much a working class part of London the site started it\'s days as the name suggests. Taking advantage of the cheap migrant labour the Black Eagle brewery was founded in the 1800\'s but the first reference to a brewery in the area can be traced back joesph truman, who in 1966 joined the bucknell brewery house of bricklane The brewery really began to make it\'s mark when the Huguenot imigrants introduced a breverage brewed using fermented hops, on the back of this success the black eagle quickly grew to be one of the largest breweries in the country.\r\n\r\nOver the years the area has benifted from the mixing pot of different cultures begining with Huguenot refugees spreading from Spitalfields, in the 17th century. Who where in turn followed by the irish, Ashkenazi Jews and, in the last century, Bangladeshis migrants.\r\n\r\nAll of these cultural influence can be seen in the local area and is reflected in the modern Truman gallery.', 'The Truman Gallery', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-truman', '', '', '2010-10-25 15:33:29', '2010-10-25 15:33:29', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/2009/12/09/the-truman/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(109, 1, '2009-12-10 00:33:20', '2009-12-10 00:33:20', 'In an attempt to better understand the brief I have set about researching the graphic elements which are uses to construct the identity of a few muesums that take there branding as seriously as the work they exhibit. The four I have choosen all go about this in different ways but one resounding simularty is that however stricking the branding is, it never detracts from the art.\r\n\r\n<strong>Whitechapel Gallery<span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"> </span></strong>\r\n\r\nThe White Chapel Gallery has been described as the “Original East End Gallery”. Located on the north side of Whitechapel high street, in the london borough of Tower Hamlets, Its shares much of the same cultural history as the old truman brewery. On our trip down to london the Whitechappel gallery was one of places of interest highest on my list. Designed by Charles Harrison Townsend it was founded in 1901 as one of the first publicly-funded galleries for temporary exhibitions in London, it has a strong track record for education and outreach projects, now focused on the Whitechapel area\'s deprived populations. It exhibits the work of contemporary artists, as well as organising retrospective exhibitions and shows that are of interest to the local community. Because of these similarities and the fact that the gallery has been recently renovated and given a fresh graphic identity I have choose it as one of my galleries to study.\r\n\r\n<strong>Type Face.</strong>\r\n\r\nThe Gallery uses a sans serif pixelated type face for their logo and headline text. I think this reflects the contemporary nature of the work exhibited in the gallery as well as completing the relative minimalist interior. This type face is often reversed out against a grey or pastel colour background.\r\n\r\n<strong>Logo Design</strong>\r\n\r\nThe logo makes use of the same font seen though out the print and web material. It is centred  both horizontally and vertically within a landscape oblong box. The text is reversed out against the colour of the box. To give the logo a square appearance the main box has a second box directly underneath it which is approximately half the hight of the first box.  I think the logo works really well because it gives the text space which adds to the overall feel of the identity.\r\n\r\n<strong>Layout</strong>\r\n\r\nThe layout of the material follows a lot of the same rules as the in the previous points. It has a modern use of geometric shapes with square playing an important role.There is also a sophisticated use of white space, one of the key elements to the identity is the positioning of key elements. The double box is always horizontally centred but left aligned.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/files/2010/03/whitechapel_poster.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-161\" src=\"http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/files/2010/03/whitechapel_poster.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"212\" /></a>', 'Muesum Research', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'muesum-research', '', '', '2010-10-25 15:33:17', '2010-10-25 15:33:17', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/2009/12/10/muesum-research/', 0, 'post', '', 0),
