(194, 1, '2010-03-25 22:55:06', '2010-03-25 22:55:06', 'Today we had a lecture from a previous student of the institute. He came to speak to us about the work he does now at seymourpowell and what he had to do to get there. Laurence Willmot graduated in 2007 and has been since working at seymourpowel. Although there was a lot of work he could not speak to us about due to the time scales involved in the projects,( The final idea may not some to fruition for several years) It was very interesting to me to find out how the design process works in such a big  company, and how there different departments work together. We were also lucky enough to get Lawrence on our own for a while to talk to him about his experiences as a student and what he done to get a job after graduating. There where 3 main points that stuck out to me;\r\n\r\n1. Enter Competitions - The more you enter the more experience you get, and the more chance you have of being successful. Laurence entered his final major project from University into a number of competitions and got a lot of positive feedback.\r\n\r\n2. Work Placements - Ultimately Laurence got the job as a result of a successful work placement over the space of two years.\r\n\r\n3. Online Portfolio - <a href=\"http://www.insightoutsight.co.uk\" target=\"_blank\">insightoutsight</a> is the name of the online collaboration Laurence is involved in. It consists of a number of his uni friends which come together to display there personal work.', 'Seymourpowell', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'seymourpowell', '', '', '2010-10-25 15:26:14', '2010-10-25 15:26:14', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/?p=194', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(170, 1, '2010-03-31 20:00:19', '2010-03-31 20:00:19', 'Today I was invited to vist the london base of the publishers Thames &amp; Hudson. Earlier in the week we had met with David Jury and a select number of BA undergraduates where given the chance to attend the MA Design Students meeting in London.We were shown round by design director Aaron Hayden.  As part of the trip we was given a tour of the offices and were offered to ask any question we had on the business. As my first visit to publishers I was intrigued at the setup of the building and the workflow of the company. Each department was separated onto a different levels within the building with designer and researchers on one level, and everything from marketing to management on others. We was told that  it was quite unusal for a publishers to still have an in-house design department.This was mainly due to the finical comitment of employing full time team. One thought that stayed with me after the trip was how fluid the workflow was throughout the company. It was commented that many of the staff had worked in other departments at one time or another so there was a good understanding of what was needed at different stages of production. I think this fact, compiled with the seemingly loyal workforce and low turn over of staff (Some staff had been at the company for nearly 50 years) cemented the fact that there seemed to be a wealth of experience at hand at each stage of a job.\r\n\r\nAaron spoke very frankly about the industry, and the problems they faced. As a student I found that I benefited from this a lot, because too often I feel companies just offer the positive aspects of a certain job or industry. We spoke in some depth about how market conditions can effect the profit margins. Things like currency fluctuation as well as the price of raw materials such as paper and oil, can all have an effect when you have an international supply chain. All of these changes can eat into a the fragile profit margins of large companies. The price of paper going up a fraction of a penny on a book that has hundred of pages which sells millions of copies can have a tremendous effect. There is also the cost/price ratio of books. Each design decision has to be scrutinised over its cost to maximise the potential margin in a book. there is no point being over elaborate with printing techniques on a cheap book aimed at the student market.\r\n\r\nI really feel that I gained a lot from this trip and I feel that it has cemented the direction I wish to pursuit in my career. I have a strong interest in digital media, and I think that by following this path I will avoid many of the negative effects of print based media.', 'Thames &amp; Hudson Trip', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'thames-hudson-trip', '', '', '2010-10-25 15:31:08', '2010-10-25 15:31:08', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/?p=170', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(178, 1, '2010-04-07 17:12:05', '2010-04-07 17:12:05', 'This is my entry for the Lakota bar in chelmsford leaflet competition. The brief was to create the artwork for their july leaflet. This is my first attempt. I tried to keep it simple and appeal to what i considered to be the audience. I particaly liked the colours against the grey.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/files/2010/05/leflet2.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-179\" src=\"http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/files/2010/05/leflet2.jpg?w=212\" alt=\"\" width=\"212\" height=\"300\" /></a>', 'Lakota Flyer Competiton', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'lakota-flyer-competiton-2', '', '', '2010-10-25 15:25:29', '2010-10-25 15:25:29', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/?p=178', 0, 'post', '', 0),
