(186, 1, '2010-05-12 20:18:32', '2010-05-12 20:18:32', 'Although a little premature, here is my evaluation of my second year.\r\n\r\nI think that the 2009/2010 academic year has been very important for me personally and professionally. As a designer I feel I have found my creative stride and have really began to embrace the opportunities that have come my way. One of the most fundamental changes has been my awareness of the historical and sociological importance of art and design in our society and how its role has changed over time. This has conceded with my greater understanding of art theory. I have also used the year to build upon my network of contacts, creating a digital portfolio, as well as a keeping a blog of my thoughts and influences.\r\n\r\nMy first task at the start for the year was to establish a base in which I could broadcast  myself to potential new clients and employers. I have tried to achieved this by creating a digital portfolio. Although I did have some prior experience in web design, I feel that this maybe the area that I have technically progressed the most. The process of researching what employers expect from a online portfolio, and what can be achieved was a very rewarding process for me. In doing so I have also been able to cement my knowledge of HTML and CSS as well as begin to understand Javascript and JQuery. I have since went on to create a blog, the main purpose of which is to record my thoughts and inspirations. I am natural very forgetful, and despite my best efforts I found that last year, I can often neglect key facts if I do not record my observation quickly. This has all changed with the use of Wordpress. I can instantly access my blog anywhere in the world and record information coherently and chronologically with the minimum amount of fuss.\r\n\r\nAfter Attending all but one of the lectures held this year concerning art history and theory, I have found that I have got a much better handle on the complex issues involved within the subject. I particularly related to the recap seminars in which we revisited some of the subjects. I found it easier to ask questions throughout the lecture as opposed to doing so after. I felt that my new found knowledge has held me in good stead when researching different designers and artist as well allowing me to take a more critical view when visiting exhibitions.\r\n\r\nOne of my biggest successes of the year was securing a summer work placement at the graphic department of the foreign exchange company Moneycorp. I currently work part-time at Stansted Airport, in the retail division of the company. After helping with design work within my department I was encouraged to send a sample of my work to head office. Although the placement is only temporary at the moment I hope that it leads on to something that is more permanent. I have also pursued placements at Thames &amp; Hudson and as well as at Wunderman where I had a placement in 2007. Although Moneycorp is my only secure placement I feel that a lot can be learnt from working in a commercial environment. I also hope that by working in a relatively small team it will give the opportunity to turn my hand to a number of tasks and potential allow me to improve my web design skills.\r\n\r\nOverall the biggest lessons I have learnt this year have ultimately  reinforced my passion for design and helped me concentrate on aspects of the industry I wish to pursue as a career.', 'PDP Summary', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'pdp-summary', '', '', '2010-10-25 15:24:14', '2010-10-25 15:24:14', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/?p=186', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(212, 1, '2010-09-22 10:26:46', '2010-09-22 10:26:46', 'Today I attended the Underground Maps exhibition at the Minories in Colchester. While I was there my class and I were lucky enough to be given a talk by the creator of the exhibition, Max Roberts. Roberts has a background in physiology but has turned his attention to underground maps in the last 10 years. His main interests lie in improving the underground maps over all readability.\r\n\r\nThe exhibition starts with a brief history of the underground maps development. Initialy the underground network consisted of a number of different lines owned by separate companies. These maps followed the historical precedent by overlaying geographically accurate information on top of an odenice survey style map. Although this method had worked for overground trains and roads maps in the past, due to londons high concentration of train lines, reading the maps became more and more difficult.This trend continued until the appointment of Harry Beck in 1931. Beck was a underground employee who first realised that the map does not need to displayed in a geographicaly accurate fashion. It was under Becks guidance that the current format for the underground map was introduced.\r\n\r\nRoberts then when on to explain the basis of his research. The main problem addressed in this research is the necessary trade off between geographical accuracy and diagrammatic simplicity. It was was about half way through the talk that he was trying to solve a redundant problem. Ultimately there would alway be a discrepancies between the two. So instead of spending a disproportionate amount of time moderately refining the map. I feel it would be better to invest that time in a new way of displaying that information all together. If for example you displayed the map in a digital format, it would be possible to view multiple maps at one time eliminating the problem altogether.', 'Max Roberts Underground Map Lecture', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'max-roberts-underground-map-lecture', '', '', '2010-10-25 15:23:51', '2010-10-25 15:23:51', '', 0, 'http://adroot.wordpress.com/?p=212', 0, 'post', '', 0);
