(233, 1, '2010-03-31 20:00:19', '2010-03-31 20:00:19', 'Today I was invited to vist the london base of the publishers Thames &amp; Hudson. Earlier in the week we had met with David Jury and a select number of BA undergraduates where given the chance to attend the MA Design Students meeting in London.We were shown round by design director Aaron Hayden.  As part of the trip we was given a tour of the offices and were offered to ask any question we had on the business. As my first visit to publishers I was intrigued at the setup of the building and the workflow of the company. Each department was separated onto a different levels within the building with designer and researchers on one level, and everything from marketing to management on others. We was told that  it was quite unusal for a publishers to still have an in-house design department.This was mainly due to the finical comitment of employing full time team. One thought that stayed with me after the trip was how fluid the workflow was throughout the company. It was commented that many of the staff had worked in other departments at one time or another so there was a good understanding of what was needed at different stages of production. I think this fact, compiled with the seemingly loyal workforce and low turn over of staff (Some staff had been at the company for nearly 50 years) cemented the fact that there seemed to be a wealth of experience at hand at each stage of a job.\n\nAaron spoke very frankly about the industry, and the problems they faced. As a student I found that I benefited from this a lot, because too often I feel companies just offer the positive aspects of a certain job or industry. We spoke in some depth about how market conditions can effect the profit margins. Things like currency fluctuation as well as the price of raw materials such as paper and oil, can all have an effect when you have an international supply chain. All of these changes can eat into a the fragile profit margins of large companies. The price of paper going up a fraction of a penny on a book that has hundred of pages which sells millions of copies can have a tremendous effect. There is also the cost/price ratio of books. Each design decision has to be scrutinised over its cost to maximise the potential margin in a book. there is no point being over elaborate with printing techniques on a cheap book aimed at the student market.\n\nI really feel that I gained a lot from this trip and I feel that it has cemented the direction I wish to pursuit in my career. I have a strong interest in digital media, and I think that by following this path I will avoid many of the negative effects of print based media.', 'Thames &amp; Hudson Trip', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '170-revision', '', '', '2010-03-31 20:00:19', '2010-03-31 20:00:19', '', 170, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2010/03/31/170-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(234, 1, '2010-03-03 11:43:52', '2010-03-03 11:43:52', 'Last week we was set the project of redesigning the artwork for one our favourite albums of the last decade. After much deliberation I chose the an album by Mark Ronson. The Song was a cover of a Maximo Park called \"<em>Apply Some Pressure</em>\" and even features the lead singer. I think I chose this song more because of the lyrics rather than anything else. Especially as when the album was released they had a particular meaning to me. A week after the project we all met up to show our work and get some feedback on what we had done, I am relatively pleased with he final out even if it isn\'t as polished as I would like it to be (being a one day project). The overall feed back was positive although there was some mention of a certain \" clinical\" style i seem to have  adopted so that is defiantly something to look out for in the future.\n\nSo Here is the Front Cover\n\n<a href=\"http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/files/2010/03/album_cover2.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-154 alignleft\" src=\"http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/files/2010/03/album_cover2.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a>', 'One Day Project', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '150-revision', '', '', '2010-03-03 11:43:52', '2010-03-03 11:43:52', '', 150, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2010/03/03/150-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(235, 1, '2010-02-19 17:12:51', '2010-02-19 17:12:51', '<strong>Confirmation of Graphic Media Practice.</strong>\n\nStarting how I mean to carry on, this is the brief for my main project in semester two.\n\n<strong>Great Speeches of the 20th century</strong>\n\nThe guardian newspaper brought together a collection of the greatest speeches of the twentieth Century. Each booklet contains an historical address and coverage of the speech from the time. The speeches are introduced by prominent figures ranging from FW de Klerck on Nelson Manuela\'s statement to the Rivonia trial to Mikhail Gorbachev on Nikitat Kruschev’s denunciation of Stalin.\n\nThe Brief: You are to select a minimum of three speeches. Consider the format that a ‘container of information’ can be; a book, booklet/pamphlet, broadsheet, pocket book, 3D object, artist-book, or photo book etc. Your design solutions could be combine illustration and/or your own/sourced photographs with the text, or it could be purely typographical or purely image based solution. Your design must work across the total collection of fourteen speeches. You are also to design the package/container/wrapper for all fourteen speeches (therefore you will need to make blind dummies for the whole series) these ‘books’ would be sold as a total collection in a selected shops such as the TATE or they may be designed as one off pieces.\n\nThis project is designed to allow you to develop your strengths and personal interests. If your passion is photography let the project be led by image, if your passion is typography let the project be led by text. If your passion is for craft, let the project be led by the handmade, and so on. Your exploration of ideas should be exciting, stimulating and test the conventions of normally excepted formats\n\nAddition research in 3 key areas will be helpful:\n<ol>\n	<li>Content: the time frame in which the speeches was written, the speaker, the country of origin, social/cultural/political context.</li>\n	<li>Physical structure: formats, materials, textures and processes.</li>\n	<li>Working processes: technical application relating to typography, print specification, illustration, photography, 3D structures.</li>\n</ol>\n<strong>Speeches</strong>\n\nWinston Churchill\n<strong><em>We shall fight on the beaches </em></strong>\nThis is the edited text of the speech delivered to House of Commons on June 4 1940.\n\nJohn F Kennedy\n<strong><em>Ask not what your country can do for you </em></strong>\nThis speech was delivered by Kennedy at his presidential inauguration on January 20 1961.\n\nNelson Mandela\n<strong><em>An ideal for which I am prepared to die </em></strong>\nThis is the full text of Mandela\'s statement from the dock at the opening of his trial on charges of sabotage, supreme court of South Africa, Pretoria, April 20 1964.\n\nHarold Macmillan\n<strong><em>No going back </em></strong>\nDouglas Hurd: In South Africa, Macmillan delivered one of the defining statements of British policy in the 20th century.\n\nFranklin D Roosevelt\n<strong><em>The only thing we have to fear is fear itself</em></strong>\nThis speech was delivered by Roosevelt at his inauguration in Washington on March 4 1933.\n\nNikita Khrushchev\n<strong><em>The cult of the individual</em></strong>\nThis is an edited version of a speech delivered by Khrushchev to the 20th congress of the Communist party of the USSR in Moscow on February 25 1956.\n\nEmmeline Pankhurst\n<strong><em>Freedom or death </em></strong>\nThis is an edited version of a speech delivered by Pankhurst in Hartford, Connecticut on November 13 1913.\n\nMartin Luther King\n<strong><em>I have a dream </em></strong>\nThis speech was delivered by King on August 28 1963 at the Lincoln Memorial, Washington.\n\nCharles de Gaulle\n<strong><em>The flame of French resistance </em></strong>\nThese speeches were delivered by Charles de Gaulle and broadcast by the BBC in 1940.\n\nMargaret Thatcher\n<strong><em>The lady\'s not for turning </em></strong>\nThis speech was delivered to the Conservative party conference in Brighton on October 10 1980.\n\nJawaharlal Nehru\n<strong><em>A Tryst with Destiny\n</em></strong>This speech was delivered by Nehru to the Constituent Assembly of India in New Delhi on August 14 1947.\n\nVirginia Woolf\n<strong><em>Shakespeare\'s sister </em></strong>\nVersions of this speech were delivered by Woolf at Girton and Newnham colleges, University of Cambridge, on October 20 &amp; 26 1928.\n\nAneurin Bevan\n<strong><em>Weapons for squalid and trivial ends </em></strong>\nThis is an edited version of a speech delivered by Bevan to the House of Commons on December 5 1956.\n\nEarl Spencer\n<strong><em>The most hunted person of the modern age </em></strong>\nThis speech was delivered at the funeral of Diana, Princess of Wales, at Westminster Abbey on September 6 1997.', 'Great Speeches of the 20th Century', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '147-revision', '', '', '2010-02-19 17:12:51', '2010-02-19 17:12:51', '', 147, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2010/02/19/147-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(236, 1, '2010-02-21 05:36:00', '2010-02-21 05:36:00', 'I found this Project particularly difficult to get into, and unfortunately we did not have much time. Because of the way the studio sessions where set up, we where only given the brief in the second half of the semester. This made it particular hard to fit in the necessary studio sessions. Despite these problems I feel that I learnt a lot about studio photography. We had a range of taught studio sessions as well as the opportunity to try it on our own.\n\nIt think one thing that I achieved in this project was the uniformity and branding of the products. I tried to make the products look very natural together and to keep a constant design running throughout. I did also try to experiment with the design of the the box but settled with a variation of a classic style.\n\nSome of the aspects I found hard about the brief was actually constructing the boxes them selves. For a support module I felt that there was a lo of work involved. Because of the nature of the products the boxes had to a least a certain size so it was hard and expensive to have the graphics printed onto a sheet of paper big enough to accommodate the large net. There was also the added issues of double sided printing as well as the weight of the paper need to maintain the structure of the box. Over all I think one of the biggest lesson I have learnt from this brief is the ability to problem solve. For all the problems above a quick and cost effective solution had to be found. I hope that my final product reflect how this was achieved.', 'Takeaway Packaging Evaluation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '202-revision', '', '', '2010-02-21 05:36:00', '2010-02-21 05:36:00', '', 202, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2010/02/21/202-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(237, 1, '2009-11-20 20:28:01', '2009-11-20 20:28:01', 'I was lucky enough to be whisked away to NewYork last week to celebrate my 21st birthday. Seeing as it is unlikely that I will be able to go again with the rest of my university class early next year I have tried to make the most of the opportunity this time round.I managed to visit the Museum of Art and Design, which I thoroughly enjoyed. One thing that did strike me about american museums is that they all seem to charge entrance fees. This seemed very unnatural from a british perspective seeing that the large majority of museums in the UK, and in Europe are donation based.\n\nGhost Stories - Nendo\n\nOne of my favorite exhibitions from the museum was “Ghost Stories” by Nendo. It consisted of several chairs aligned randomly on the floor. But due to a very clever bi of design he managed to substitute the wooden legs of the chair with plastic giving the illusion of the chairs floating in a eire mist. I think the reason I liked this piece so much is that it appears to trick the eye. At first glance you see chairs and wonder how the effect has been achieved. The use of contrasting materials and the process of allowing the audience to second guess your work is defiantly a quality I would like to achieve in some of my designs.\n\nThis Is For You - Rob Ryan\n\nThe second exhibition found interesting was that of Rob Ryan. Ryan had several piece on show but my favorite was a two story window hanging. I think that drew my attention first was the pure scale of the piece, the second was its intricacy. Although the media used was simple, the detail was not. What I liked most about the piece, apart from the elegance of the design its self, was the way it looked in the light. Because of the cutting you saw both the designs, media behind it (the window) and the shadow it cast.', 'New York New York!!', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '188-revision', '', '', '2009-11-20 20:28:01', '2009-11-20 20:28:01', '', 188, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2009/11/20/188-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(238, 1, '2010-02-12 04:56:28', '2010-02-12 04:56:28', 'Old Truman Evaluation\n\nOverall I have been very pleased with my progress on the main project for semester one. The real guts of the project was to try and get a sense of what brick lane was then and what is now. And Ultimately translate that into a coherent brand. I tried to stay with a very clean set of designs because I wanted to steer away from the temptations of over complicating the final work with grunge textures and backgrounds. I think that its was a good progression for me too, Mainly because it was a lot harder to make something like sophisticated than to make it look trendy. I think this move can really summaries the direction that my design focus has been moving in for the last couple of months.\n\nI have been trying to concentrate on the benefits of using grids systems when flowing text into document in indesign.  As well as some of the more technical aspects of typography. One of my biggest achievements I feel is that I have come up with a unique way of presenting the folding poster. By using a slim design and aligning the text I have achieved legibility on both surfaces when closed. (As apposed to the writing being upside down) I Was also very pleased with the colour palette I used through out the project. I think that this was one of the strongest elements of the the brand identity\n\nAreas where I could have improved through out the project was my ability to record my progression as I went along. I found myself spending hours in front of the computer tweaking designs without properly recording the development. I think that this could be detrimental to my final grade as it is a key aspect of the design process.', 'Old Truman Evaluation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '199-revision', '', '', '2010-02-12 04:56:28', '2010-02-12 04:56:28', '', 199, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2010/02/12/199-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(239, 1, '2010-02-01 19:51:15', '2010-02-01 19:51:15', 'Again it has been to long between posts but as a quick update this is the latest version of my poster design. the brief for the design is a A3 poster which folds down to A5 size. The front must promote an event from one of the months listing. In this case the showing of the film \'The Krays\' at the \'Old Trumen\' (new name by the way) the back must be a list of the full months events. I\'ve tried to stick to the same colour palate as list before using the pink for the cinema events. See the link below for a look.\n\n<a href=\'http://adroot.files.wordpress.com/2010/02/a3_poster_slim2.pdf\'>A3_Poster_Slim2</a>', 'The Poster', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '130-revision', '', '', '2010-02-01 19:51:15', '2010-02-01 19:51:15', '', 130, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2010/02/01/130-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(240, 1, '2010-01-15 23:24:34', '2010-01-15 23:24:34', 'This is just a quick update on my logo development. After much consideration and a lot of indecision I have come to the conclusion that my new identity for the Truman Brewery needs a strong mark. I have tried to capitalise on the quality of the type face I am using. I was hoping that just the pure fact of writing the name of the gallery in the font that is gill, would be enough to fill the mind of the viewer, (Consciously or unconsciously) with connotations of all things british. but unfortunately, for a number of reasons, (mainly the stipulation in the brief that I must create a logo) that the design is lacking.\n\nMy alternative is to introduce a mark which is instantly recognisable that I can use in a more subtle way to embed the brand of the gallery on different aspects of the brief.  I have settled with the silhouette of a water-lily. It is my best attempt so far to marry the british and asian cultures of the local area. I am still undecided on a colour, for the time being I will replicate the logo in all 5 of the colours used.\n\n<a href=\"http://adroot.files.wordpress.com/2010/01/lotus_colour2.jpg\"><img src=\"http://adroot.files.wordpress.com/2010/01/lotus_colour2.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"132\" class=\"aligncenter size-medium wp-image-123\" /></a>', 'Logo Development', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '125-revision', '', '', '2010-01-15 23:24:34', '2010-01-15 23:24:34', '', 125, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2010/01/15/125-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(241, 1, '2009-12-10 00:33:20', '2009-12-10 00:33:20', 'In an attempt to better understand the brief I have set about researching the graphic elements which are uses to construct the identity of a few muesums that take there branding as seriously as the work they exhibit. The four I have choosen all go about this in different ways but one resounding simularty is that however stricking the branding is, it never detracts from the art.\n\n<strong>Whitechapel Gallery<span style=\"font-weight:normal\"> </span></strong>\n\nThe White Chapel Gallery has been described as the “Original East End Gallery”. Located on the north side of Whitechapel high street, in the london borough of Tower Hamlets, Its shares much of the same cultural history as the old truman brewery. On our trip down to london the Whitechappel gallery was one of places of interest highest on my list. Designed by Charles Harrison Townsend it was founded in 1901 as one of the first publicly-funded galleries for temporary exhibitions in London, it has a strong track record for education and outreach projects, now focused on the Whitechapel area\'s deprived populations. It exhibits the work of contemporary artists, as well as organising retrospective exhibitions and shows that are of interest to the local community. Because of these similarities and the fact that the gallery has been recently renovated and given a fresh graphic identity I have choose it as one of my galleries to study.\n\n<strong>Type Face.</strong>\n\nThe Gallery uses a sans serif pixelated type face for their logo and headline text. I think this reflects the contemporary nature of the work exhibited in the gallery as well as completing the relative minimalist interior. This type face is often reversed out against a grey or pastel colour background.\n\n<strong>Logo Design</strong>\n\nThe logo makes use of the same font seen though out the print and web material. It is centred  both horizontally and vertically within a landscape oblong box. The text is reversed out against the colour of the box. To give the logo a square appearance the main box has a second box directly underneath it which is approximately half the hight of the first box.  I think the logo works really well because it gives the text space which adds to the overall feel of the identity.\n\n<strong>Layout</strong>\n\nThe layout of the material follows a lot of the same rules as the in the previous points. It has a modern use of geometric shapes with square playing an important role.There is also a sophisticated use of white space, one of the key elements to the identity is the positioning of key elements. The double box is always horizontally centred but left aligned.\n\n<a href=\"http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/files/2010/03/whitechapel_poster.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-161\" src=\"http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/files/2010/03/whitechapel_poster.jpg?w=300\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"212\" /></a>', 'Muesum Research', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '109-revision', '', '', '2009-12-10 00:33:20', '2009-12-10 00:33:20', '', 109, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2009/12/10/109-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(242, 1, '2009-12-09 23:27:09', '2009-12-09 23:27:09', 'The main project we are working on this semester is the rebranding of the Old Truman Gallery in bricklane, the gallery hosts wide range of events and exhibitons through out the year, and is rewnond for it\'s colourful cultural heritage. The site where the gallery now stands has it\'s roots burried deep in the history of the east end.\n\nVery much a working class part of London the site started it\'s days as the name suggests. Taking advantage of the cheap migrant labour the Black Eagle brewery was founded in the 1800\'s but the first reference to a brewery in the area can be traced back joesph truman, who in 1966 joined the bucknell brewery house of bricklane The brewery really began to make it\'s mark when the Huguenot imigrants introduced a breverage brewed using fermented hops, on the back of this success the black eagle quickly grew to be one of the largest breweries in the country.\n\nOver the years the area has benifted from the mixing pot of different cultures begining with Huguenot refugees spreading from Spitalfields, in the 17th century. Who where in turn followed by the irish, Ashkenazi Jews and, in the last century, Bangladeshis migrants.\n\nAll of these cultural influence can be seen in the local area and is reflected in the modern Truman gallery.', 'The Truman Gallery', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '104-revision', '', '', '2009-12-09 23:27:09', '2009-12-09 23:27:09', '', 104, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2009/12/09/104-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(244, 1, '2010-12-07 11:38:10', '2010-12-07 11:38:10', 'Today I had the chance to meet the recently formed creative collective, The <a title=\"Hidden Dingbat\" href=\"http://www.hiddendingbat.co.uk\" target=\"_blank\">Hidden Dingbat</a>. Consisting of  the creative skills of Phil ___ and Lauren____ two  graduates of  Colchester Institute. We started the workshop with a quick presentation, explaining how they had come to form the collective and their design education background. They then went on describe some of the trials and tribulations of the 3rd year and the problems that we can expect to encounter.\n\nSome of the main points;\n<ul>\n	<li>Social networking - Get your self known.</li>\n	<li>Visit London - D&amp;AD lectures, exhibitions etc.</li>\n	<li>Make the most of Colchester - 15 Queen Street, Minories, Slat Space</li>\n	<li>Be nice, be positive</li>\n	<li>Be generous with your time and ideas</li>\n	<li>Speak to practitioners</li>\n	<li>PDP Like there is no tomorrow</li>\n</ul>\nThe rest of the work shop was based around the idea of creating brands for start up company trying to capitalise on the empty shops left by the recession. My brief was to design a logo for \'Kidz corner\'.I think the main things i took away from the work shop was the need to act proactivly in my self promotion work', 'Hidden Dingbats', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '243-revision', '', '', '2010-12-07 11:38:10', '2010-12-07 11:38:10', '', 243, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2010/12/07/243-revision/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(245, 1, '2010-10-25 15:22:50', '2010-10-25 15:22:50', 'Today is my first post of the third year. The summer has been a exciting time for me, I managed to gain some work experience with Moneycorp, which proved be very productive. A design I had been working while in knightsbridge has been chosen for use in the airport. All though the initial brief was only for an A3 poster the final print is well over two metres (pictures to follow).\r\n\r\nI have also been working hard on my research for my FMP and dissertation. After much deliberation I think I have settled on a subject and for the most part a title. I have been spending a lot of time research information design, mapping and infographics, with particular reference to the internet. I feel this subject best sums up my career aspirations and should hopefully give me a platform in which to display my skills. I hope that due to the nature of the work and it\'s reliance on a large number of graphic applications, such as typography grid layouts ect, that it will accommodate most of the areas I am interested.\r\n\r\nIn the third year so far there has been a lot of talk specialising in a particular discipline. The main thinking behind this is that it can dramatically improves your chances of employment, If you focus all your efforts in one field, potentially you are a stronger candidate for a particular role as a posed to a \'Jack of all trades\' designer which can turn their hands to most tasks but is a master of none. The point I take difference to is that because a designer can work with image placement, grids, typography, illustration and web design etc that they do not have a area specialty. Unfortunately my argument fell apart because I could not find a role which satisfied most of these skills,This was until I found information design.', 'Summer Update', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '206-revision-2', '', '', '2010-10-25 15:22:50', '2010-10-25 15:22:50', '', 206, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/journal/2010/10/25/206-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
