(271, 1, '2011-02-21 13:43:17', '2011-02-21 13:43:17', '[caption id=\"attachment_128\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"264\" caption=\"&quot;Breakfast With Mother&quot; Internet Week Europe 2010\"]<a href=\"http://www.adroot.co.uk/portfolio/files/2010/11/portrait.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-128 \" title=\"Internetweek\" src=\"http://www.adroot.co.uk/portfolio/files/2010/11/portrait-264x300.jpg\" alt=\"&quot;Breakfast With Mother&quot;\" width=\"264\" height=\"300\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nHello, I am a British graphic media student, currently in my final year of study. My main interests revolve around the careful construction of colour, letterforms and pixels.\r\n\r\nI like to design objects that are folded and pressed, but I also partake in my fair share  of tag and query writing too. I am a self-confessed geek and have a passion for an open, <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_neutrality\">neutral</a> internet, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2010/nov/11/google-vint-cerf-internet?INTCMP=SRCH\">bursting</a> with <a href=\"http://data.gov.uk/\">data</a> and <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OM6XIICm_qo\">possibilities</a>.\r\n\r\nAs a designer, I take great pride in the expert treatment of typography and imagery. I feel that refining these points makes all the difference to a project.\r\n\r\nThis website has been lovingly coded using HTML, CSS, PHP and a pinch of JavaScript. Powered by <a href=\"http://www.wordpress.org\">WordPress</a>, the framework of the layout is the great descendant of a <a href=\"http://wpshower.com/\">Wpshower</a> theme. The other design and content however are proudly my own.', 'Aaron', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2-revision-43', '', '', '2011-02-21 13:43:17', '2011-02-21 13:43:17', '', 2, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/portfolio/2-revision-43/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(258, 1, '2010-12-18 09:46:46', '2010-12-18 09:46:46', 'Yesterday was my first D&amp;AD Lecture, and even with the tube strike I made the pilgrimage to London. The style of todays lecture was Pecha Kucha, a japanese idea in which a presenter shows a set number of slides within a short amount time. It seemed like the perfect introduction the lectures because I got to see a number of different designers work in a relatively short amount of time. I particularly liked the work of  <a href=\"http://www.itsnicethat.com/\">It’s Nice That</a>, <a href=\"http://www.mr-bingo.org.uk/\">Mr Bingo</a> and <a href=\"http://www.katemoross.com/\">Kate Moross</a>.  Not only because what they presented was exceptional work but because they done it with a sense of humor.\r\n\r\nApart from the general experience of the event, (I felt smarter, just through sitting in the same room as so many creative people)  I learnt a  few things about making a presentation engaging and interesting.\r\n\r\nOne of the most interesting questions raised was in the closing statement by Graham Fink. After asking the audience to remember a memory from their childhood, then stating that that no cell in the human body is more than about 7 years old. Mr Think then eloquently points out that any memory from our childhood has no physical correlation with our bodies today, concluding \"who the f**k do you think you are?\".', 'D&AD Presidents Lecture', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '210-revision-10', '', '', '2010-12-18 09:46:46', '2010-12-18 09:46:46', '', 210, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/portfolio/210-revision-10/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
