(232, 1, '2010-12-16 12:56:18', '2010-12-16 12:56:18', 'Yesterday was my first D&AD Lecture, and even with the tube strike I made the pilgrimage to London. The style of todays lecture was Pecha Kucha, a japanese idea in which a presenter shows a set number of slides within a short amount time. It seemed like the perfect introduction the lectures because I got to see a number of different designers work in a relatively short amount of time. I particularly liked the work of  It’s Nice That, Mr Bingo and Kate Moross.  Not only because what they presented was exceptional work but because they done it with a sense of humor.\r\n\r\nApart from the general experience of the event, ( I felt smarter, just through sitting in the same room as so many creative people)  I learnt a  few things about making an engaging presentation.  \r\n\r\nOne of the most interesting questions raised was in the closing statement by Graham Fink. After asking the audience to remember a memory from their childhood, then describing that no cell in the human body is much more than seven years old. Mr Think elequently points out that any memory from our childhood has no physical correlation with our bodies today, finally asking<blockquote>\"who the fuck do you think you are?\".</blockquote>\r\n\r\n', 'D&AD Presidents Lecture', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '210-revision-5', '', '', '2010-12-16 12:56:18', '2010-12-16 12:56:18', '', 210, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/portfolio/210-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
