(259, 1, '2010-12-30 18:25:15', '2010-12-30 18:25:15', 'Yesterday was my first D&amp;AD lecture and, even with the tube strike, I made the pilgrimage to London. The style of today’s lecture was Pecha Kucha, a Japanese idea in which presenters show 20 slides for 20 seconds each (<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pecha_Kucha\">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pecha_Kucha</a> ). It seemed like the perfect introduction to the lectures because I got to see a number of different designers’ work, in a relatively short amount of time. I particularly liked the work of <a href=\"http://www.itsnicethat.com/\">It’s Nice That</a>, <a href=\"http://www.mr-bingo.org.uk/\">Mr Bingo</a> and <a href=\"http://www.katemoross.com/\">Kate Moross</a>. Not only because what they presented was exceptional work, but because they have done it with a sense of humour.\r\n\r\nApart from the general experience of the event – I felt smarter, just through sitting in the same room as so many creative people – I learnt a few things about making a presentation engaging and interesting.\r\n\r\nOne of the most interesting questions raised was in the closing statement by Graham Fink. After asking the audience to remember a memory from their childhood, he stated that no cell in the human body is more than about 7 years old. Mr Fink then eloquently pointed out that any memory from our childhood has no physical correlation with our bodies today, concluding “who the f**k do you think you are?”.', 'D&AD President\'s Lecture', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '210-revision-11', '', '', '2010-12-30 18:25:15', '2010-12-30 18:25:15', '', 210, 'http://www.adroot.co.uk/portfolio/210-revision-11/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
