7;d most like in your armory. <em>Easy peasy</em>. The contest does end this coming Monday, the 11th, so don&#8217;t dawdle.</p><p>Okay, so they&#8217;re not exactly breaking the mold as far as internet contests go, but it&#8217;s a small price to pay for a free WordPress theme, right?<em> </em>Let us know if you win, so we can enjoy it vicariously through you!</p><div class=\"tentblogger-rss-footer\"><p>You just finished reading <a href=\"http://wpcandy.com/?p=16727\">Inspired Magazine is giving away 26 WordPress themes</a> on <a href=\"http://wpcandy.com\" title=\"WPCandy WordPress community news\">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 08 Apr 2011 22:38:47 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Ryan Imel\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:25;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:2:{s:0:\"\";a:5:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:87:\"WPCandy: WPBundle unbundles, offers new pricing structure, and separates from WooThemes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:27:\"http://wpcandy.com/?p=16721\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:101:\"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/wpcandy/~3/7vZRwqD2kGc/wpbundle-unbundles-offers-new-pricing-structure\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2715:\"<p><a href=\"http://wpcandy.com/?p=16721\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-16723 alignnone\" title=\"WPBundle pricing news (teaser)\" src=\"http://wpcandy.com/files/2011/04/wpbundlebundle-teaser.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" /></a></p><p>WPBundle <a title=\"WPBundle pricing structure announcement\" href=\"http://www.wpbundle.com/2011/new-wpbundle-pricing/\">announced</a> this week that they would be making individual theme purchases available, where previously only their 10 theme bundle could be purchased. Individual themes are available for $50 each, though the bundle of all themes is still around for just $200, down from the previous $250 price tag. Mini-bundles were also teased, though no details are available yet regarding just what these will include.</p><p>The team stresses that individual theme sales include support, updates, child themes, and access to their icon set, same as the previous bundle did. Liam McKay described the reasons for the decision on their blog:</p><blockquote><p>From the start of the project we’ve had a lot of people requesting individual theme sales. We’ve never been against the idea, but there was a few reasons why we didn’t feel right doing this, one of which was our name! It felt strange moving away from bundles, because of that, but we understand the demand and need for cheaper options.</p></blockquote><p>The announcement also included the news that WPBundle is no longer partnering with WooThemes.</p><p><span id=\"more-16721\"></span></p><p>McKay says there are no hard feelings over the split, but that with the new direction WPBundle is headed WooThemes &#8220;didn&#8217;t want to be part of the new direction as they have to focus their attention on their own products.&#8221; WPBundle will now use their own sales and support system, which they are in the process of implementing now.</p><p>Also, have a read through our past WPBundle coverage: WPBundle is one of the first WordPress shops that we were able to watch pretty much from <a title=\"WPCandy coverage of WPBundle\" href=\"http://wpcandy.com/covers/wpbundle\">when they began</a>.</p><p>While we&#8217;re on this topic, what is your stance on theme pricing? Do you prefer buying in bulk via a bundle or a membership, or buying individual themes? If you were calling the shots, what would you say? Where&#8217;s the sweet spot between profitability and user friendliness?</p><div class=\"tentblogger-rss-footer\"><p>You just finished reading <a href=\"http://wpcandy.com/?p=16721\">WPBundle unbundles, offers new pricing structure, and separates from WooThemes</a> on <a href=\"http://wpcandy.com\" title=\"WPCandy WordPress community news\">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 08 Apr 2011 21:50:56 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Ryan Imel\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:26;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:2:{s:0:\"\";a:5:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:65:\"WPCandy: WordPress All in One for Dummies now available on Amazon\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:27:\"http://wpcandy.com/?p=16713\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:110:\"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/wpcandy/~3/L_kPMvniorQ/wordpress-all-in-one-for-dummies-now-available-on-amazon\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1845:\"<p><img class=\"size-full wp-image-11280 alignnone\" title=\"WordPress All-in-One for Dummies\" src=\"http://wpcandy.com/files/2011/01/wpallinone-teaser.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"198\" /></p><p>Who&#8217;s a dummy? Are you a dummy? Okay, are you a dummy compared to the smart folks who joined forces to write <em>WordPress All in One for Dummies</em>? Insulted or not, if you wanted to you could now pick the book up from Amazon since <a title=\"WordPress All in One for Dummies on Amazon\" href=\"http://www.amazon.com/WordPress-All-One-Dummies-Sabin-Wilson/dp/0470877014/\">it&#8217;s available there this week</a>.</p><p>We&#8217;ve mentioned it <a href=\"http://wpcandy.com/reports/wordpress-all-in-one-now-available-for-pre-order-on-amazon\">once</a> or twice before, but it&#8217;s worth repeating. Lisa Sabin-Wilson, the author of <em>WordPress for Dummies</em>, recruited four other prominent WordPress community members to join her in writing this new book: Cory Miller (of <a href=\"http://ithemes.com/\">iThemes</a>), Kevin Palmer (of <a href=\"http://www.convertiv.com/\">Convertiv</a>), Andrea Rennick (of <a href=\"http://wpebooks.com/\">WPeBooks</a>) and Michael Torbert (of the <a href=\"http://wordpress.org/extend/plugins/all-in-one-seo-pack/\">All in One SEO Pack</a>). Each author tackled a section devoted to their own area of specialty, and while I haven&#8217;t read it yet I&#8217;m anticipating quite a bit.</p><p>Have you snatched up a copy and dug into <em>All in One</em> yet? If so, share your thoughts on it in the comments.</p><div class=\"tentblogger-rss-footer\"><p>You just finished reading <a href=\"http://wpcandy.com/?p=16713\">WordPress All in One for Dummies now available on Amazon</a> on <a href=\"http://wpcandy.com\" title=\"WPCandy WordPress community news\">WPCandy</a>. Please consider leaving a comment!</p><p></p></div>\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 08 Apr 2011 17:03:18 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Ryan Imel\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:27;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n	\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:2:{s:0:\"\";a:5:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:38:\"Publisher Blog: AARP Blog on WordPress\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:43:\"http://publisherblog.automattic.com/?p=1361\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:70:\"http://publisherblog.automattic.com/2011/04/08/aarp-blog-on-wordpress/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2659:\"<p>The AARP has launched their blog on <a href=\"http://vip.wordpress.com/hosting\">WordPress.com VIP</a>.</p>\n<p>To recall the sentiment of Beth Carpenter&#8217;s post &#8220;<a href=\"http://blog.aarp.org/2011/01/25/boomers-on-facebook-twitter-yep-sure-are/\">Baby Boomers on Twitter? Yep, sure are</a>&#8220;, to that we say, <strong>Baby Boomers on WordPress? Yep, sure are.</strong></p>\n<p>Welcome!</p>\n<p><a h